bourg, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France":"Neufbourg, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, Frankrig","France":"Frankrig"},"nl":{"about 1175–":"circa 1175–Overleden","1175–Female":"1175–Overleden","1185–1251":"1185–1251","1165–1234":"1165–1234","1190–1279":"1190–1279","1190–1287":"1190–1287","1190–Female":"1190–Overleden","1158–1216":"1158–1216","1160–1185":"1160–1185","1190":"1190","1165":"1165","1175":"1175","1251":"1251","1185":"1185","1160":"1160","1216":"1216","1158":"1158","1279":"1279","1234":"1234","1287":"1287","about 1175":"circa 1175","Abt 1190":"circa 1190","Neufbourg, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France":"Neufbourg, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, Frankrijk","France":"Frankrijk"},"en":{"about 1175–":"about 1175–Deceased","1175–Female":"1175–Deceased","1185–1251":"1185–1251","1165–1234":"1165–1234","1190–1279":"1190–1279","1190–1287":"1190–1287","1190–Female":"1190–Deceased","1158–1216":"1158–1216","1160–1185":"1160–1185","1190":"1190","1165":"1165","1175":"1175","1251":"1251","1185":"1185","1160":"1160","1216":"1216","1158":"1158","1279":"1279","1234":"1234","1287":"1287","about 1175":"about 1175","Abt 1190":"about 1190","Neufbourg, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France":"Neufbourg, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Crespin,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Carlos, Raul, Vidal, Adelina, Alfonso, Amador, Andres, Aniceto, Delfino, Emilio.","Spanish (<b>Crespín</b>): variant of   Crispin  .","French: from the Latin personal name <i>Crispinus</i> (see   Crispin  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Crispin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Pedro, Alicia, Fernando, Manuel, Rafael, Adolfo, Alfredo, Ana, Areli, Candita.  French Adrien, Andre, Eugenie, Francoise.","English; Spanish (<b>Crispín</b>): from the personal name Middle English <i>Crispin</i>, Spanish <i>Crispín</i>, from Latin <i>Crispinus</i>, derived from <i>crispus</i> ‘curly-haired’ (see   Crisp  ). This name was especially popular in France in the early Middle Ages, having been borne by a Christian saint who was martyred at Soissons in  AD <i>c.</i> 285 along with a companion, <i>Crispinianus</i> (whose name is a further derivative of the same word). Compare   Crespin   and 3 below.","English (of Norman origin): from Old French and Middle English <i>crespin</i>, <i>crispin</i> ‘curly-haired’, also found as <i>Crepin</i>; see   Crippin  . It is difficult to tell this apart from the personal name in 1 above. According to Lanfranc, archbishop of Canterbury (1070–1089), the Norman Gilbert Crispin was the first man to receive this nickname, and two of his sons adopted it as their surname. His grandson Gilbert Crispin became abbot of Westminster in 1085. Members of the Norman family were said to have inherited a shock of hair that stood up stiffly like a bristly pine, as though the name derived from Latin <i>crispus pinus</i>, but this derivation is a medieval invention."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabeau Crespin, Dame de Livarot was born about 1175, in France, her father, Guillaume III du Bec-Crespin, was 11173 and her mother, Eve d'Harcourt, Dame de Lisors, was 16. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Robert II de Neufbourg, Seigneur de Livarot."},"et":{"about 1175–":"umbes 1175–Surnud","1175–Female":"1175–Surnud","1185–1251":"1185–1251","1165–1234":"1165–1234","1190–1279":"1190–1279","1190–1287":"1190–1287","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1158–1216":"1158–1216","1160–1185":"1160–1185","1190":"1190","1165":"1165","1175":"1175","1251":"1251","1185":"1185","1160":"1160","1216":"1216","1158":"1158","1279":"1279","1234":"1234","1287":"1287","about 1175":"umbes 1175","Abt 1190":"umbes 1190","Neufbourg, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France":"Neufbourg, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1175–":"noin 1175–Kuollut","1175–Female":"1175–Kuollut","1185–1251":"1185–12